    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-01-29T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-01-29T08:00:00-05:00" n="89"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d89">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857/308</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-01-29T14:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 29, 1917, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 30, 7.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4948. Following note received from the Foreign Office: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p rend="right">Berlin, January 26, 1917.</p>
                        <p>The undersigned has the honor to inform his excellency Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_GJW1">James W. Gerard</persName>, Ambassador of the
                            United States of America, in reply to the note of Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_GJC1">J. C. Grew</persName>, dated December 11, 1916
                            (Foreign Office No. 14829), relative to the sinking of the British
                            steamer <hi rend="italic">Trevarrick</hi> by a German submarine as
                            follows:</p>
                        <p>According to the facts as ascertained by the German naval authorities the
                            British steamer <hi rend="italic">Trevarrack</hi>, not <hi rend="italic"
                                >Trevarrick</hi>, was stopped by a German submarine on the morning
                            of November 16, 1916; the crew left the steamer without further delay
                            when the signal to stop was given and sailed away from the steamer in
                            their boats. The vessel was then sunk as an enemy vessel after it had
                            been searched.</p>
                        <p>The undersigned requests that the above may be brought to the cognizance
                            of the American Government and avails himself [etc.]</p>
                        <p rend="right">
                            <persName corresp="#p_SW1">Stumm</persName>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
